subSubSection.paragraph:
Diagnosis.
Both sexes present depressed setal bases associated with tubercles covering the carapace surface. Males (
Figs 32–33
) can by distinguished by the short, twisted embolus, RTA nearly triangular with acute tip, and the presence of a distal spine on the prolateral side of femora II and III. Females (
Fig. 31
) can be also distinguished by the narrow anterior epigynal hood and the well separated copulatory openings and the very wide median field.

